Can Crop Switching Help Mitigate the Effect of Climate on Agricultural Productivity in the Fruitful Rim?

WSU School of Economic Sciences - Pullman, WA




Nicholas Potter, Michael Brady, Kirti Rajagopalan

Washington State University

October 19, 2018

Temperature and irrigated land rents

Climate effects on profits and land values

  • Mendelsohn, Nordhaus, and Shaw (1994): hedonic regression exploiting climate variation across counties (omitted variable bias is a problem).
  • The effect on irrigated counties is different than non-irrigated counties (Schlenker, Hanemann, and Fisher 2005).

(Figure 4 from MNS 1994.)

Fixed-effects models for cleaner identification

  • Deschênes and Greenstone (2007) use a fixed-effects model and find that higher temperatures positively affect profit.
  • Fixed-effects models capture short-term adaptation to weather, but not long term adaptations to changing climate.

(Figure 2 from DG 2007.)

Yield response is non-linear

  • In a fixed-effects model modeling the distribution of temperatures, Schlenker and Roberts (2009) demonstrated a sharp non-linearity.

(Figure 1 from SR 2009.)

Little evidence of adaptation

  • Burke and Emerick (2016) employ “long differences” and find little evidence of adaptation in variety hardiness, input adjustment, or crop switching.
(But they focus on corn, soybeans, cotton, wheat, hay, and rice in the southeast U.S.)

Is estimating climate effects enough?



Hallegatte, Hourcade, and Ambrosi (2007) state

“This paper aims at proposing a way to get round the intrinsic deadlocks of the economic assessment of climate change impacts (absence of consistent baseline scenario and of a credible description of adaptation behaviours under uncertainty.”

Research Question




What is the effect of climate on agricultural productivity when producers can mitigate impacts by switching crops?

Where do producers have a large crop-mix choice set?

Consider the Western Fruitful Rim (irrigated counties in ID, WA, OR, CA, AZ):

  • Production in a diverse set of high-value crops (e.g. apples, wine grapes, berries, etc…).
  • Irrigation fed by snowpack melt unlike eastern U.S. and dryland farming regions.

These two factors allow for a large set of viable crop mixes.

No study yet focused on this area, though some have focused on the United States as a whole.

What are irrigated rents?

The rental value of irrigated agricultural land ($ per acre):

  • Rents reflect the expected value of productivity over the period of the lease.
  • Expectations about land productivity reflect expectations about climate and ability to adapt in the short run.
  • This is the first study to make use of irrigated rents that we are aware of.

Data

  • Gridded temperature and precipitation data at the 6km scale from 2008-2016 (VIC hydrological model).
  • Projected temperature and precipitation from 2020-2099 based on MACAv2-METDATA (Abatzoglou, 2011).
  • Silt, clay, and sand ratios at ‘map-unit’ resolution (SSURGO).
  • By county, agricultural cash rents from 2008-2016 and irrigated acres in 2012 (USDA).
  • By county, satellite-based crop acreage estimates for 2008-2016 (USDA Crop Data Layer).

A primer on climate projections

  • Representative Concentration Pathways (RCPs) are scenarios for concentrations of Carbon, Nitrogen, and Sulfur.
  • There are multiple climate models that incorporate a range of assumptions. Here we use the CNRM-CM5 model, a mid-range model.

Empirical Model


Our empirical model follows Schlenker and Roberts (2009) and Schlenker, Hanemann, and Fisher (2005):

\[\ln y_{it} = \sum \limits_{j = 0,3,6,...}^{32+} \beta_j \Phi_{it,j} + z_{it} \delta + c_i + \varepsilon_{it}\]

where:

  • \(\Phi_{it,j}\) is the proportion of growing season hours spent in the temperature range \([j-3, j]\).
  • \(z_{it}\) is growing season days, rain, rain squared, and a set of second-order time-by-state dummies.
  • \(c_i\) is county fixed-effects. In the cross-sectional analysis this is a set of time-invariant variables that include soil and population density.
  • \(\varepsilon_{it}\) is a spacially correlated error term.

But is crop-switching a viable mitigation strategy?


Problems:

  • Could employ a multinomial choice model, but there are 109 crop categories in the USDA CDL.
  • Aggregating up to crop categories (e.g. vegetables, field crops) is too broad.

Potential Solution:

  • Use matching to find the 2012 analogue to 2040 climate for each county.

Matching benefits


  • The difference in outcomes is an estimate of the effect of climate on agricultural productivity, but with the additional benefit of reduced omitted variable bias.
  • Differences in crop mix provides an estimate of crop-switching as an adaptation.
  • Other comparisions between matched counties allow for Hallegatte’s “credible description of adaptation behaviors.”

What do we expect?

Two hypotheses:

  • H0\(_A\): the effect estimated via matching will lie between the cross-section and and fixed-effect estimates.
  • H0\(_B\): the crop-mix distributions of matched counties are not statistically different from each other. This would imply little advantage to switching crops.

Matching model


We use a genetic matching algorithm from Sekhon (2011):

\[\hat{Y}_i(1) = Y_m(0), \\ \; m = \arg \min \limits_{j \in J} \; GMD(X_{1i}, X_{0j}, k).\]

where:

  • \(X_{1i} = \{\pi(\Phi_{1i}, Z_{1i}), \Phi_{1i}, Z_{1i}\}\) is the set of covariates for county \(i\) in the projected climate scenario of 2040.
  • \(X_{0i}\) is similarly defined for the current period.
  • \(\pi(\Phi_{1i}, Z_{1i})\) is the propensity score.
  • the covariates share the same symbols as in the cross-sectional analysis.

  • The proportion of acres planted to each crop is a distribution of crop-mix.
  • Kolmogorov-Smirgov test for difference in continuous distributions suggests no difference.

So can crop-switching mitigate climate effects?

  • There are few significant differences in the distribution of crop mix between matched counties, suggesting that switching does not provide a benefit. This could be due to:

    1. the effect of climate in 2040 being too small to make switching worthwhile, and
    1. significant frictions that make switching costly.

Primary contributions


In this paper we:

  • use a novel approach to estimate the effect of climate on crop-mix distribution to determine the viability of crop-switching as a climate adaptation strategy.
  • provide the first estimate of climate effects on agricultural productivity using rents, a superior measure to profits and land values.
  • examine the effects of climate in areas where there are multiple crops and where irrigation is the primary water source.

Going forward

We hope to address:

  • changing snowpack and water availability
  • current water use in the cross-sectional and fixed-effects approaches
  • downstream transportation and processing infrastructure frictions
  • general equilibrium effects
  • empirical measures of differences in crop-mix.
